# Sign in with any OIDC provider

Nocturne's social login is a generic OpenID Connect client. Any provider that publishes a
standard discovery document works — Nocturne fetches
`{issuer}/.well-known/openid-configuration` and wires up the authorization, token, and
userinfo endpoints automatically. [Google](/docs/authentication/google) and
[GitHub](/docs/authentication/github) have their own step-by-step guides; this page covers
everything else: Okta, Auth0, Keycloak, Authentik, Microsoft Entra ID, Zitadel, and so on.

## The callback URL

Whichever provider you use, register this redirect (callback) URL with it:

```
https://your-instance.com/api/auth/oidc/callback
```

Replace `your-instance.com` with your actual Nocturne domain. This is the same URL for
every provider — only the credentials differ.

## Two ways to configure providers

Nocturne reads providers from one of two places:

1. **Admin UI (database-backed)** — add and edit providers at runtime from
   **Settings > Admin > OIDC Providers**. No restart needed. This is the default.
2. **Operator config (`appsettings` / environment)** — declare providers in configuration.
   When one or more providers are configured this way, Nocturne **bypasses the database
   entirely and hides the management UI**. Use this for declarative, infrastructure-as-code
   deployments.

<Callout type="info" title="Pick one, not both">
  As soon as <code>Oidc:Providers</code> has at least one entry in configuration, the
  database-backed providers and their management UI are ignored. Manage providers either
  through the admin UI <em>or</em> through configuration — not a mix.
</Callout>

### Option A: the admin UI

1. Register the callback URL (above) with your provider and obtain a **client ID** and
   **client secret**.
2. Sign in to your Nocturne instance as an admin.
3. Go to **Settings > Admin > OIDC Providers** and click **Add Provider**.
4. Fill in the fields (see the field reference below) and **Save**.

The new sign-in button appears on your login page immediately.

### Option B: configuration

Declare providers under the `Oidc:Providers` array. Keep the client **secret** out of
`appsettings.json` — supply it through user-secrets or an environment variable.

```jsonc
"Oidc": {
  "Providers": [
    {
      "Name": "Okta",
      "IssuerUrl": "https://your-org.okta.com",
      "ClientId": "0oaxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx",
      "Scopes": ["openid", "profile", "email"],
      "DefaultRoles": ["readable"],
      "Icon": "https://your-org.okta.com/favicon.ico",
      "ButtonColor": "#007dc1",
      "DisplayOrder": 0,
      "IsEnabled": true
    }
  ]
}
```

Supply the secret separately, by index:

```bash
# Local development (user-secrets)
dotnet user-secrets set "Oidc:Providers:0:ClientSecret" "your-client-secret"

# Production (environment variable — note the double underscores)
Oidc__Providers__0__ClientSecret=your-client-secret
```

## Field reference

| Field | Required | Description |
|-------|----------|-------------|
| **Name** | Yes | Display name on the login button (e.g. *Okta*). |
| **Issuer URL** | Yes | The provider's issuer. Nocturne appends `/.well-known/openid-configuration` to discover the rest. |
| **Client ID** | Yes | OAuth2 client ID registered with the provider. |
| **Client Secret** | Yes | OAuth2 client secret. Supply via secrets manager / env, never in `appsettings.json`. |
| **Scopes** | No | Scopes to request. Defaults to `openid`, `profile`, `email`. |
| **Default Roles** | No | Roles assigned to new users from this provider. Defaults to `readable`. |
| **Icon** | No | One of the known slugs `google`, `apple`, `microsoft`, `github`, or a URL to a logo. Anything else falls back to a generic icon. |
| **Button Color** | No | CSS color for the button background. |
| **Display Order** | No | Lower numbers appear first. Defaults to `0`. |
| **Enabled** | No | Whether the provider is offered for login. Defaults to `true`. |

## Common issuer URLs

| Provider | Issuer URL |
|----------|------------|
| Okta | `https://your-org.okta.com` |
| Auth0 | `https://your-tenant.us.auth0.com` |
| Keycloak | `https://your-host/realms/your-realm` |
| Authentik | `https://your-host/application/o/your-app-slug/` |
| Microsoft Entra ID | `https://login.microsoftonline.com/{tenant-id}/v2.0` |
| Zitadel | `https://your-instance.zitadel.cloud` |
| Google | `https://accounts.google.com` |

<Callout type="tip" title="Not sure of the issuer?">
  Open <code>https://your-provider/.well-known/openid-configuration</code> in a browser. If
  it returns JSON with <code>authorization_endpoint</code> and <code>token_endpoint</code>,
  the part before <code>/.well-known/...</code> is your issuer URL.
</Callout>

## New accounts and roles

When someone signs in through a provider for the first time, Nocturne creates an account
and assigns the provider's **Default Roles** (`readable` unless you change it). Adjust this
list to control what new users can do before an admin grants them more access.

Providers configured through the admin UI also support **claim mappings** — pairs of
*(OIDC claim name → Nocturne claim name)* — for providers that emit non-standard claim
names. Most providers need no mapping when they return the standard `email`, `name`, and
`sub` claims.

